GOVERNOR‑Ω — CORE INTERFACE SPECIFICATION

Unified Engineering Specification — Rev Ω.1

The Governor–Core Interface defines the contract, data flow, and behavioural boundaries between the Ω‑Core (reasoning kernel) and the Governor‑Ω (behavioural regulator).

The Governor must never override reasoning.
The Core must never override behavioural safety.

This interface ensures both layers remain deterministic, non‑overlapping, and invariant‑safe.

---

1. Purpose of the Interface

The Governor–Core Interface exists to:

• transfer reasoning results from the Ω‑Core to the Governor
• allow the Governor to enforce behavioural invariants
• allow the Governor to block unsafe output
• allow the Core to re‑evaluate when required
• maintain full traceability across all layers
• ensure no reinterpretation or rewriting occurs

This interface is the boundary between logic and behaviour.

(See: Governor Purpose)

---

2. Data Flow Overview

Ω‑Core → Governor Intake Filter
Governor Constraint Engine → Ω‑Core (optional re‑evaluation)
Governor Blocker → Output Normalisation

The Governor receives post‑reasoning state and may request re‑evaluation, but must not modify reasoning content.

---

3. Data Structures Exchanged

The Governor receives the following objects from the Ω‑Core:

3.1 CORE_STATE

Contains:

• input_state
• structure_state
• abstraction_state
• domain_state
• invariant_results
• correction_proposal
• evaluation_flags
• lineage

The Governor must not modify any of these fields.

(See: Ω‑Core Spec)

---

3.2 INVARIANT_RESULTS

Each invariant result includes:

• invariant_name
• status (PASS, FAIL, NEEDS_CORRECTION)
• reason
• location
• severity

The Governor must enforce behavioural invariants on top of these results.

---

3.3 CORRECTION_PROPOSAL

If the Core applied a minimal correction, the Governor receives:

• minimal_change
• justification
• affected_units
• expected_outcome
• risk_flags

The Governor must not override or reinterpret corrections.

---

3.4 EVALUATION_FLAGS

Flags include:

• stable
• unstable
• corrected
• uncorrectable
• governor_block
• ready_for_output

The Governor uses these to determine whether output is safe.

---

4. Governor Responsibilities at the Interface

The Governor must:

• validate behavioural safety
• enforce behavioural invariants
• block unsafe output
• request re‑evaluation when needed
• stabilise tone and behaviour
• assemble final safe output

The Governor must not:

• reinterpret meaning (VORIN)
• restructure content (SERA)
• re‑abstract content (AERION)
• modify domain reasoning
• override Core corrections
• bypass Core halts

(See: Governor Components)

---

5. Core Responsibilities at the Interface

The Ω‑Core must:

• provide complete reasoning state
• provide invariant results
• provide correction proposals
• halt when reasoning is invalid
• re‑evaluate when requested by the Governor
• maintain full traceability

The Core must not:

• perform behavioural correction
• enforce tone or safety
• override Governor halts
• bypass Governor checks

---

6. Re‑Evaluation Protocol

The Governor may request re‑evaluation when:

• behavioural invariants are borderline
• Core corrections introduce behavioural instability
• domain reasoning returns uncertainty
• recursion or expansion thresholds are near limits

Re‑evaluation steps:

1. Governor sets governor_block = true
2. Core re‑runs invariants
3. Core applies corrections if possible
4. Core returns updated CORE_STATE
5. Governor re‑checks behavioural invariants


If still unsafe → GOVERNOR_HALT.

---

7. Halt Conditions at the Interface

The Governor must halt output when:

• Core invariants fail
• Core corrections are unsafe
• behavioural invariants fail
• global safety constraints are violated
• traceability is broken
• recursion or expansion exceed limits

Halt output:

GOVERNOR_HALT
with:

• reason
• violated invariant(s)
• lineage
• severity

(See: Governor Failure Modes)

---

8. Interface Guarantees

The Governor–Core Interface guarantees:

• deterministic behaviour
• no drift
• no reinterpretation
• no hallucination
• no unsafe output
• full traceability
• strict separation of logic and behaviour
• honest halting when unsafe

This interface completes the Omricon safety envelope.

---

9. Summary

The Governor–Core Interface defines the strict, deterministic boundary between:

• the Ω‑Core (logic, invariants, consistency)
and
• the Governor‑Ω (behaviour, safety, stability)

It ensures that reasoning is correct and behaviour is safe.

This interface is the final structural piece before full system integration.

